<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-147-160  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 160.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Desktop Publishing  Feb 5 1990 v4 n6 p1(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The ISO standard for font information. (font attributedescription)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><TEXT>The ISO Standard For Font Information THE FREEWHEELING market may not beready to think about it, but some companies would like to see a stablestandard for describing font information in a document.andP;  We are speakinghere, not about the format for storing font outlines--be it Adobe's, Apple'sor some other--but about the manner of describing a font's attributes so thatan electronic document can be displayed or printed with good fidelity whenthe original fonts used in its creation are not available.andP;  The InternationalStandard Organization (ISO) has undertaken to solidify a means of describingfonts that will not change every time a vendor releases a bug fix or anupgrade.andM;Hashing out a single font standard that addresses all languages, all fontsand all computer systems is no easy task.andP;  The concensus process is as much apolitical struggle as it is a technical one, for in order to be accepted byall parties, it must take into account the concerns of all participants.andP;  Theresult in this case, as so often happens, is a compromise between what somewould like and what everyone can agree to.andP;  The result, despite itslimitations, is a standard that offers a device- and vendor-independentmethod of exchanging font information as part of a document.andP;  If it isaccepted, we suspect its importance will grow as users struggle with documentexchange in a digital world.andO;</TEXT></DOC>